<item>
            <title>[GROOVY-2555] Calling abstract super method causes stack overflow instead of compiler error</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/GROOVY-2555</link>
                <project id="12318123" key="GROOVY">Groovy</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;I accidentally wrote some code that called an abstract method on a superclass and received a StackOverflowError instead of a compiler error (the method was calling itself despite the &quot;super.&quot;...). Doing the same thing in Java results in an error like &quot;abstract method theMethod() in A cannot be accessed directly&quot; and I think Groovy should probably do something similar (see the attached test case).&lt;/p&gt;</description>
                <environment></environment>
        <key id="12814046">GROOVY-2555</key>
            <summary>Calling abstract super method causes stack overflow instead of compiler error</summary>
