                    <fixVersion>1.6-beta-1</fixVersion>
                                        <due></due>
                            <votes>0</votes>
                                    <watches>0</watches>
                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14464287" author="md5" created="Wed, 30 Jan 2008 02:17:29 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thinking about this a little bit, I guess this has to be caught at runtime, not in the compiler. Otherwise, it wouldn&apos;t be possible to dynamically add an implementation of the abstract method to the superclass to make the subclass call work (as pathological and ill-considered as that sounds)...&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14478050" author="paulk" created="Tue, 15 Apr 2008 20:07:03 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Now if an abstract method is encountered, it is treated as if it isn&apos;t there, i.e. via the normal missing method logic.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
